# RAG-First Note Conventions

Project notes are consumed by LLM agents and retrieval pipelines. Keep them chunk-friendly and self-contained.

## Frontmatter schema (required keys)

```yaml
---
id: <type>-<slug>            # e.g., adr-2026-04-26-adopt-moc
type: moc | adr | changelog | backlog | runbook | doc | meeting
project: <Project Name>
status: draft | active | proposed | accepted | superseded | done | blocked | dropped
owner: <person>
created: YYYY-MM-DD
updated: YYYY-MM-DD
tags: [domain/<x>, tech/<y>, area/<z>]
links: ["[[Projects/<Project Name>/MOC]]"]
---
```

- `id` is globally unique and matches the filename slug.
- `links` lists strong graph neighbors using OFM wikilinks.
- `tags` use slash-namespaced taxonomy for filter-friendly retrieval.

## Body structure

- First section is always `## TL;DR` (1-3 sentences, self-contained).
- Then stable H2 headings specific to the note `type` (see governance rule).
- Each H2 section should be independently useful as a retrieval chunk: restate the subject if needed.
- Use short paragraphs or bullets. Avoid nested headings deeper than H3.

## Linking

- OFM wikilinks only: `[[Projects/<Project Name>/decisions/<note>]]`.
- No `[label](path.md)` for internal links.
- Cross-reference related notes at the bottom under `## Related` when not already in `links` frontmatter.

## Self-containment

- State `project`, `type`, and core context at the top of the body (the TL;DR).
- Avoid pronouns without antecedents. Prefer explicit nouns for retrieval clarity.
- Do not rely on external context that is not linked.

## Agent behavior

- Always populate and keep `updated` current on edit.
- Keep section order stable; never reorder H2 sections.
- When adding a new note, mirror the template from `_System/Templates/` exactly.
